Engines may stall FAA urgently orders inspection of 2,000 Boeing airliners - Xinhua
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic airliners registered in the United States. The reason is that the air check valve of the above-mentioned airliners may cause the engine to stop in the air after it is corroded.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of air parking of the engines of 737NG and 737 Classic passenger aircraft, so it has made emergency inspection requirements. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for seven days or more and passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after being put back into flight.
The FAA warned that if the stage 5 check valve of all two engines of the airliner is corroded, it may jam in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and be unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, air operators must replace this key component before the airliner is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the new crown outbreak led to a reduction in travel demand. As a result, many passenger aircraft were mothballed or used less, making "check valves more vulnerable to corrosion".
At the same time, Boeing said that air operators have been advised to inspect the airliners involved in the instructions. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger aircraft owned by major US air operators usually fly multiple times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger aircraft were grounded. With the recent slow growth of passenger travel demand, some passenger aircraft have been put back into operation.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
In a statement, the air operator said that one of its airliners was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled and the airliner finally made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said that the engine of the airliner has been replaced and the engines of six airliners have been inspected in accordance with the instructions of the Federal Aviation Administration.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that there were no engine stalls associated with air check valves on their airliners.
Four airliners owned by American Airlines will be inspected and 28 airliners owned by United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its airliners, but did not say whether there had been engine stalls.
A number of media reports that the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737 MAX in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger aircraft was subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year and resumed production in May.
FaA Administrator Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA "made a mistake" in the supervision of Boeing with regard to the 737 MAX airliner.
