For the first time, the United States launched a countervailing investigation against China on the basis of "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate".
In response to the recent announcement by the US Department of Commerce, it has decided to launch an anti-dumping countervailing investigation against tie (bundle belt) products originating in China and launch an investigation into the "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate" project.
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the United States has filed a case to investigate the so-called "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate" project in a countervailing case, which China firmly opposes.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a special press release in this regard on the evening of the 23rd, saying that China implements a managed floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand, adjusted with reference to a basket of currencies, and that the market plays a decisive role in the formation of the exchange rate.
The press release stressed that, on the whole, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable and balanced level and is not undervalued.
Since 2005, the cumulative appreciation of the RMB against the US dollar has exceeded 17%.
According to the data released by the Bank for International Settlements, from the beginning of 2005 to May 2020, the effective exchange rate of the RMB name appreciated by 38% and the real effective exchange rate appreciated by 49%, making it the strongest currency among the G20 economies and one of the currencies with the largest appreciation worldwide.
The Ministry of Commerce pointed out that the exchange rate issue exceeds the authority of members to conduct countervailing investigations in accordance with the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In February this year, the United States amended its regulations to conduct countervailing investigations into the exchange rates of other countries. It has been suspected of violating the WTO rules of the WTO and has been opposed by many parties.
According to the press release, even in accordance with US regulations, there are a large number of errors in the content of the applicant's complaint, which does not have the necessary countervailing elements such as financial assistance, benefit granting and exclusivity.
China urges the United States to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate".
Affected by the further rise in tensions between China and the United States, the offshore and onshore RMB exchange rates against the US dollar fell sharply at one point in the session on the 22nd, both falling below the 7.0 yuan mark against the US dollar.
Whether the move by the US Department of Commerce is intended to force up the renminbi is worth paying attention to.
The spot exchange rate of the RMB against the US dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd, closing at 6.9961.
