Kokoxiri Tibetan antelope enters relocation season - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) A reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Kokoxiri Administration Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelope that had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area of the Kokoxiri hinterland to give birth were successively ending giving birth and beginning to return to their original habitat with their children.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station showed that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelope led three Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 km of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliangbei Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelope has begun to move back.
Experts have analyzed that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope cubs in the returning sheep accounted for one-quarter to one-fifth of the overall number of Tibetan antelope groups.
Lien Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early days of relocation, Tibetan antelope faced a high risk of predation, so the number of cubs in the sheep will be relatively small, and there may even be no cubs."
According to the statistics of the Kokoxiri Administration Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelope relocated is generally increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelope relocated was 4,860, an increase of 338 over 2018.
Lien Xinming said, "It is expected that the relocation of Tibetan antelope will end at the beginning of September this year, and the number of Tibetan antelope relocated is still expected to continue to increase."
The Tibetan antelope is a protected animal at the national level.
At the end of May each year, Tibetan antelope from the source of the Sanjiang River in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet and Alshan Mountain in Xinjiang go to Zhuonai Lake, located in the hinterland of Kokoxiri, to lay lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert in the protection of Tibetan antelope in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said, "The relocation of Tibetan antelope is the process by which female Tibetan antelope return to their habitat with their cubs after giving birth. At first, the relocation group that left the birth site is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelope will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope groups, the reporter learned that the Kokoxiri Administration Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has recently arranged for staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation areas.
If a Tibetan antelope group is found to be trying to cross the highway, the mountain rangers will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the sheep to safely pass through the wildlife passageway and ensure that they are as little disturbed by humans as possible on the way back.
