Brazilian study shows that hydroxychloroquine is not effective in the treatment of mild to moderate new crown pneumonia -- ScienceDaily
Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is not effective in patients with mild to moderate new crown pneumonia.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients in 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted clinical trials. They mainly compared the treatment effect of using hydroxychloroquine alone or combined with other antibiotic azithromycin, and analyzed whether it would help improve the condition of patients with mild and moderate new crown pneumonia.
The results showed that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on viscera.
This study was jointly completed by a number of authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as Hospital Israel Albert Einstein, Cardiology Hospital and Hospital S-rio-Libans, together with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and the Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network (BRCNet).
