The APEC Member Trade Ministers' Meeting said it would accelerate the promotion of regional economic recovery - Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) A video conference of trade ministers of APEC members was held on July 25. The meeting pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the regional economy and accelerate the realization of a flexible, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the organizer of this year's APEC Leaders' Informal Meeting.
A joint statement issued after the meeting said that the trade ministers of APEC members recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time.
All parties pledged to ensure that the emergency measures taken to deal with the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, and will not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while complying with the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In their statement, the trade ministers of APEC members pledged to strengthen cooperation to promote the flow of necessary goods and services, promote connectivity by strengthening the flexibility of the supply chain, and minimize the interference to the flow of medical materials, food and agricultural products in order to respond to the epidemic.
The trade ministers of APEC members agreed that it is necessary to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict the trade of necessary goods, and reiterated their commitment to promote the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration said that all economies will ensure that the trade measures they take in response to the epidemic comply with WTO regulations, and pledged to take action in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion in order to promote the necessary flow of goods under the epidemic.
Azmin Ali, Minister of International Trade and Industry of Malaysia, who presided over the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating APEC's post-2020 cooperation vision is advancing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC related meetings in the form of video, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging physical meetings when APEC leaders meet informally at the end of the year.
