France increases military investment in space - Xinhua
French Defense Minister Florence Pali said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to the space defense budget and develop space military forces to guard against "unfriendly moves" that may be carried out by other countries in outer space.
Pali told the Provence newspaper on the same day that between 2019 and 2025, the expenditure budget for French space military projects will increase from the previously proposed 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion U.S. dollars) to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion U.S. dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act from 2019 to 2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation satellites and communications satellites in the future, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites and improve the level of modernization of space surveillance radars.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a space military command and an "aviation and space force" will be established within the French Air Force.
Pali said that she will officially announce the establishment of the space force when she visits a military school in Salon, Provence region, later.
Pali said that the space force is affiliated with the Air Force and will have a strength of 500 by 2025.
"Gone is the idea that space serves the common interests of science. Today, space is a place for countries to compete for global hegemony," she said.
Pali reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to thoroughly recognize the threats we may face."
Pali recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She claimed that the "sneak peek" was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denies this claim.
Pali said that France will "soon" have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting "the black hands behind those unfriendly moves".
French media believe that France sought to establish a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill to establish the Pacific Air Force last February.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act last December, approving the establishment of the sixth army of the United States, the Pacific Air Force.
Some experts are concerned that these US initiatives have accelerated the pace of militarization of US space and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
