Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to be smashed playing in the college playground to sue the university authorities after receiving compensation?
2020-07-26 05: 01: 11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
The playground was smashed, and the child sued the school authorities after receiving compensation.
Zhao Yifan, Correspondent of this newspaper
Three-year-old Xiaowen was playing in a university playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen made compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground where the incident was located make an apology and pay a total of 20,000 yuan for medical expenses and compensation for moral damage.
Recently, after hearing the case, the Haidian District People's Court of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen had made compensation. According to the judgment, the plaintiff's claim was rejected.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation in 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks caused by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents are active in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, after that, Chen Mou, a member of the softball team, got rid of the ball while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiaowen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believed that the facilities of the school stadium did not comply with the relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The fault of the school led to the occurrence of the above incident, which led to great physical and mental suffering to Xiaowen, as well as great suffering to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground and posted management regulations and training notices, informing it that it was necessary to maintain a safe distance from the training ground and remind it to pay attention to its own safety when entering the playground. The plaintiff could not prove that the school had "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations", so it did not agree to compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the venue of the incident was a venue open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a safety and security obligation for the management of the playground, this safety and security obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground and has fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations. Chen also compensated Xiaowen for more than 2,000 yuan for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses in accordance with the compensation agreement reached before. The two parties agreed to resolve the dispute in one go.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, which was unfounded in the law. The court ruled against all the plaintiff's claims.
After the sentencing, neither party appealed, and the judgment has now entered into force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as the manager of a public place, has the obligation of safety and security. In the case of damage caused by the behavior of a third party, the third party shall bear the tort liability, while the manager of a public place who fails to fulfill the obligation of safety and security shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
According to the judge, because as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place and foresee the dangers and damage that may occur, so he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the degree of damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the occurrence of damage is the lowest. Therefore, the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding safeguard obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified entrants in the playground open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of the school should be appropriate to the social activities they engage in. Specifically, they should mainly take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform them of hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on the managers of public places.
If the school has adopted the establishment of a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it may be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for the infringement of a third party, even if the managers of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is used as a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, the managers may also recover compensation from the third party after assuming the supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should no longer expand the scope of the claim after he has received compensation from the direct infringer.
