A schematic diagram of the preparation technology of new mixed matrix membranes
Shang Rui, a reporter for this newspaper, reported that a few days ago, the atmospheric environment and bioenergy team of Tianjin University made significant progress in the "membrane separation method to capture carbon dioxide", and successfully developed a new mixed matrix film preparation technology, greatly improving the carbon dioxide capture performance of membrane materials.
The relevant results have been published as the cover article of the international journal Greenhouse Gas: Science and Technology.
The "greenhouse effect" is a major environmental problem that perplexes human development, while carbon dioxide emissions are the culprit of the "greenhouse effect".
How to efficiently capture and utilize the carbon dioxide emitted by humans is the focus of scientists.
The "membrane separation method" is an emerging carbon dioxide capture technology. It separates carbon dioxide gas with the help of membrane materials, which has the characteristics of high efficiency, energy conservation and simple operation.
How to make membrane materials "breathe deeply" and improve the efficiency of gas separation is the bottleneck difficulty of using membrane separation method to capture and collect carbon dioxide.
The research team of Tianjin University innovated its ideas and explored the influence of different solvents on the separation performance of membrane gas through repeated experiments.
The experimental results show that using N-methylpyrolactone as the preparation solvent, the distribution of carbon nanotubes in the produced membrane materials is more uniform and "more breathable", effectively improving the gas separation efficiency and rate of the membrane materials.
The carbon dioxide separation performance of mixed matrix membranes prepared with this new technology is close to the current theoretical separation upper limit of such membrane materials.
"The new technology provides a new idea for the membrane separation method to capture and collect carbon dioxide."
